                                           Associated Legendre                                           Polynomials                                           The ALegendr function returns                                           the required functions of the                                           associated Legendre                                           polynomials. This function is                                           required to provide the                                           scattering angle dependency of                                           the scattered intensity.   [Associated Legendre Polynomials]       [p,t]=ALegendr(q, nmax)                                           calculates the required                                           functions from order 1 to                                           nmax, for angle(s) q, by                                           upwards recursion. The returns                                           p and t are nmax-by-nq                                           matrices, where nq is the                                           dimension of the vector q,                                           each column representing the                                           results for one angle.                                                       [Return to Index]    ALegendr.m    % ALegendr      the angular dependent Associated Legendre Polynomials    %       [p,t]=ALegendr(ang, nmax)    %       produces matrices p and t with rows n=1 to n=nmax    %       for pi and tau functions rescpectively.    % Written by and copyright    %       Dave Barnett    %       Optical Engineering Group    %       Dept. of Electrical and Electronic Engineering    %       Loughborough University    %       20th November 1996    function [p,t] = ALegendr(ang, nmax)    p(1,:) = ones(1,size(ang,2));    t(1,:) = cos(ang);    p(2,:) = 3*cos(ang);    t(2,:) = 2*cos(ang).*p(2,:)-3;    for n=3:nmax            p(n,:) = ((2*n-1)*cos(ang).*p(n-1,:) - n*p(n-2,:))/(n-1);            t(n,:) = n*cos(ang).*p(n,:) - (n+1)*p(n-1,:);    endThis page designed by the author of the m-files, David Barnett